   616                                  ;
   617                                  ;       OS.COM
   618                                  ;
   619                                  ;       The operating system file is assembled at the start of the data area of the floppy disk image, which
   620                                  ;       immediately follows the directory. This corresponds to logical cluster 2, even though the physical address of
   621                                  ;       this sector on the disk varies depending on the disk type. The os.com file consists of two parts, the OS loader
   622                                  ;       and the OS kernel. The Loader is 16-bit code that receives control directly from the boot sector code after the
   623                                  ;       OS.COM file is loaded into memory. The kernel is 32-bit code that receives control after the Loader has
   624                                  ;       initialized protected-mode tables and 32-bit interrupt handlers and switched the CPU into protected mode.
   625                                  ;
   626                                  ;       Our loader addressability is set up according to the following diagram.
   627                                  ;
   628                                  ;       SS -----------> 007b00  +-----------------------------------------------+ SS:0000
   629                                  ;                               |  Boot Stack & Boot PSP (Unused)               |
   630                                  ;                               |  256 = 100h bytes                             |
   631                                  ;       SS:SP --------> 007c00  +-----------------------------------------------+ SS:0100  07b0:0100
   632                                  ;                               |  Boot Sector (vstart=0100h)                   |
   633                                  ;                               |  1 sector = 512 = 200h bytes                  |
   634                                  ;                       007e00  +-----------------------------------------------+
   635                                  ;                               |  File Allocation Table (FAT) I/O Buffer       |
   636                                  ;                               |  9 x 512-byte sectors = 4,608 = 1200h bytes   |
   637                                  ;                               |                                               |
   638                                  ;       CS,DS,ES -----> 008f00  |  Loader PSP (Unused)                          | DS:0000
   639                                  ;                               |                                               |
   640                                  ;       CS:IP --------> 009000  +-----------------------------------------------+ DS:0100  08f0:0100
   641                                  ;                               |  Loader Code                                  |
   642                                  ;                               |  2 sectors = 1024 = 400h bytes                |
   643                                  ;                       009400  +-----------------------------------------------+ DS:0500
   644                                  ;
   645                                  ;=======================================================================================================================
   646                                  ;-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
   647                                  ;
   648                                  ;       OS Loader                                                               @disk: 004200   @mem: 009000
   649                                  ;
   650                                  ;       This code is the operating system loader. It resides on the boot disk at the start of the data area, following
   651                                  ;       the directory. The loader occupies several clusters that are mapped in the file allocation tables above.
   652                                  ;       The loader executes 16-bit instructions in real mode. It performs several initialization functions such as
   653                                  ;       determining whether the CPU and other resources are sufficient to run the operating system. If all minimum
   654                                  ;       resources are present, the loader initializes protected mode tables, places the CPU into protected mode and
   655                                  ;       starts the console task. Since the loader was called either from the bootstrap or as a .com file on the boot
   656                                  ;       disk, we can assume that the initial IP is 0x100 and not perform any absolute address fix-ups on our segment
   657                                  ;       registers.
   658                                  ;
   659                                  ;-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
   660                                                          cpu     8086                                            ;assume minimal CPU
   661                                  section                 loader  vstart=0100h                                    ;use .COM compatible addressing
   662                                                          bits    16                                              ;this is 16-bit code
   663 00000000 0E                      Loader                  push    cs                                              ;use the code segment
   664 00000001 1F                                              pop     ds                                              ;...as our data segment
   665 00000002 0E                                              push    cs                                              ;use the code segment
   666 00000003 07                                              pop     es                                              ;...as our extra segment
   667                                  ;
   668                                  ;       Write a message to the console so we know we have our addressability established.
   669                                  ;
   670 00000004 BE[2900]                                        mov     si,czStartingMsg                                ;starting message
   671 00000007 E81200                                          call    PutTTYString                                    ;display loader message
   672                                  ;
   673                                  ;       Now we want to wait for a keypress. We can use a keyboard interrupt function for this (INT 16h, AH=0).
   674                                  ;       However, some hypervisor BIOS implementations have been seen to implement the "wait" as simply a fast
   675                                  ;       iteration of the keyboard status function call (INT 16h, AH=1), causing a max CPU condition. So, instead,
   676                                  ;       we will use the keyboard status call and iterate over a halt (HLT) instruction until a key is pressed.
   677                                  ;       By convention, we enable maskable interrupts with STI before issuing HLT, so as not to catch fire.
   678                                  ;
   679 0000000A B401                    .30                     mov     ah,EBIOSFNKEYSTATUS                             ;keyboard status function
   680 0000000C CD16                                            int     EBIOSINTKEYBOARD                                ;call BIOS keyboard interrupt
   681 0000000E 7504                                            jnz     .40                                             ;exit if key pressed
   682 00000010 FB                                              sti                                                     ;enable maskable interrupts
   683 00000011 F4                                              hlt                                                     ;wait for interrupt
   684 00000012 EBF6                                            jmp     .30                                             ;repeat until keypress
   685                                  ;
   686                                  ;       Now that a key has been pressed, we signal the system to restart by driving the B0 line on the 8042
   687                                  ;       keyboard controller low (OUT 64h,0feh). The restart may take some microseconds to kick in, so we issue
   688                                  ;       HLT until the system resets.
   689                                  ;
   690 00000014 B0FE                    .40                     mov     al,EKEYBCMDRESET                                ;8042 pulse output port pin
   691 00000016 E664                                            out     EKEYBPORTSTAT,al                                ;drive B0 low to restart
   692 00000018 FB                      .50                     sti                                                     ;enable maskable interrupts
   693 00000019 F4                                              hlt                                                     ;stop until reset, int, nmi
   694 0000001A EBFC                                            jmp     .50                                             ;loop until restart kicks in
   695                                  ;-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
   696                                  ;
   697                                  ;       Routine:        PutTTYString
   698                                  ;
   699                                  ;       Description:    This routine sends a NUL-terminated string of characters to the TTY output device. We use the
   700                                  ;                       TTY output function of the BIOS video interrupt, passing the address of the string in DS:SI
   701                                  ;                       and the BIOS teletype function code in AH. After a return from the BIOS interrupt, we repeat
   702                                  ;                       for the next string character until a NUL is found. Note that we clear the direction flag (DF)
   703                                  ;                       with CLD before the first LODSB. The direction flag is not guaranteed to be preseved between
   704                                  ;                       calls within the OS. However, the "int" instruction does store the EFLAGS register on the
   705                                  ;                       stack and restores it on return. Therefore, clearing the direction flag before subsequent calls
   706                                  ;                       to LODSB is not needed.
   707                                  ;
   708                                  ;       In:             DS:SI   address of string
   709                                  ;
   710                                  ;       Out:            DF      0
   711                                  ;                       ZF      1
   712                                  ;                       AL      0
   713                                  ;
   714                                  ;-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
   715 0000001C FC                      PutTTYString            cld                                                     ;forward strings
   716 0000001D AC                      .10                     lodsb                                                   ;load next byte at DS:SI in AL
   717 0000001E 84C0                                            test    al,al                                           ;end of string?
   718 00000020 7406                                            jz      .20                                             ;... yes, exit our loop
   719 00000022 B40E                                            mov     ah,EBIOSFNTTYOUTPUT                             ;BIOS teletype function
   720 00000024 CD10                                            int     EBIOSINTVIDEO                                   ;call BIOS display interrupt
   721 00000026 EBF5                                            jmp     .10                                             ;repeat until done
   722 00000028 C3                      .20                     ret                                                     ;return
   723                                  ;-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
   724                                  ;
   725                                  ;       Loader Data
   726                                  ;
   727                                  ;       Our only "data" is the string displayed when system starts. It ends with ASCII carriage-return (13) and line-
   728                                  ;       feed (10) values. The remainder of the boot sector is filled with NUL. The boot sector finally ends with the
   729                                  ;       required two-byte signature checked by the BIOS. Note that recent versions of NASM will issue a warning if
   730                                  ;       the calculated address for the end-of-sector signature produces a negative value for "1024-($-$$)". This will
   731                                  ;       indicate if we have added too much data and exceeded the length of the sector. Note also that since we are at
   732                                  ;       the end of a "file" (os.com) and not the boot sector, there is no end-of-sector marker (0x55 0xaa) here.
   733                                  ;
   734                                  ;-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
   735 00000029 5374617274696E6720-     czStartingMsg           db      "Starting OS",13,10,0                           ;starting message
   735 00000032 4F530D0A00         
   736 00000037 00<rept>                                        times   1024-($-$$) db 0h                               ;zero fill to end of sector
